  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are often also malleable. Both ductility and malleability are physical properties of metals that describe their ability to deform under stress without breaking. \n\n- **Ductility** refers to a metal's ability to be drawn into a wire. A ductile metal can undergo a significant amount of plastic deformation before it fractures.\n\n- **Malleability** refers to a metal's ability to be hammered or rolled into thin sheets. A malleable metal can be flattened into thin sheets without breaking.\n\nThe underlying reason for both properties is the same: the ability of the metal's crystal lattice to deform plastically through the movement of dislocations. Metals that are ductile tend to have a high density of dislocations, which allows them to deform significantly before fracturing. This same property usually makes them malleable as well.\n\nExamples of metals that are both ductile and malleable include gold, silver, copper, and aluminum. However, there can be exceptions, and the extent of ductility and malleability can vary between different metals.",
